The requirement for “special reasons” is intended to restrict the circumstances in which the court will order discovery (or interrogatories under r 
22.1(3)
). The precise character of the restriction is essentially impressionistic. Indeed, some cases contain statements that the expression “special reasons” has a plain, unambiguous and common meaning that does not require judicial gloss: Beadle v Director General of Social Security (1985) 60 ALR 225 at 228 ; Stavert v Stavert [1998] NSWSC 487;  BC9803463 ; Priest v New South Wales [2006] NSWSC 12;  BC200600180 at [128] . On this approach, each case must be determined having regard to its own particular circumstances and the task of the court is to consider those circumstances and to determine whether it is satisfied that special reasons exist: see generally Percy v General-Motors Holden’s Pty Ltd [1975] 1 NSWLR 289 ; Boyle v Downs [1979] 1 NSWLR 192 .
